## Peer Attacks

### Spencer’s Attack on Jacob

| Date | April 15, 2025 |
| :---- | :---- |
| Target | pizza-service.vviseguy.click/api/auth |
| Classification | OWASP A2 \- Cryptographic Failures |
| Severity | Low |
| Description | Analysis of the jwt token structure revealed all of the user roles and permissions data, though token manipulation wasn’t successful. |
| Images | ![][image2] |
| Corrections | Minimize sensitive data in token payloads and ensure robust signature verification so other users do not have access to credentials. |

| Date | April 15, 2025 |
| :---- | :---- |
| Target | pizza-service.vviseguy.click/api/order |
| Classification | OWASP A4 \- Insecure Design |
| Severity | Medium  |
| Description | The server was returning a 500 internal server error when processing a negative price value, indicating some improper input validation. Rather than validating and rejecting, the application crashes. |
| Images | ![][image3] |
| Corrections | Implement proper server-side validations for all numeric inputs. Validate that prices are positive values before processing orders. |

### Jacob’s Attack on Spencer

| Item | Result |
| :---- | :---- |
| Date | April 15th, 2025 |
| Target | pizza-service.pizzapalace.click |
| Classification | A03:2021-Injection |
| Severity | High (9) |
| Description | The endpoint `PUT /api/auth` for user info updating does not sanitize the `email` field. This, combined with the structure of the query allows a malicious user to overwrite the username and password of any userID of their choosing. |
| Images | ![A Successful Attack][image4] ![Success\!][image5] (That hashed password is a salted hash for “password”) |
| Corrections | Remove the `Update user` endpoint entirely as it is not used in the app, or use parameterized queries instead of string concatenation. Moving the “GET” portion of the query to the start might also be a good place to go. |

## Combined summary of learnings

Our penetration tests revealed some serious security vulnerabilities in JWT Pizza. The most concerning was probably the SQL injection vulnerability that Jacob found in the email field that allows malicious users to overwrite the usernames and passwords of any user ID. It’s a huge authorization bypass that could potentially compromise the entire application.  
Default credentials exposure was another huge finding, with the admin credentials being discoverable through the `/api/docs` endpoint. This allowed a lot of unauthorized admin access and credential creation for users that shouldn’t have access to those functionalities.  
Input validation was another problem that we had, with the application crashing when processing negative prices. Additionally, JWT tokens that were produced contained excessive role information. While the signature verification stays intact, sensitive information remains visible. Our findings indicate a lot of common security pitfalls on the backend, mostly relating to improper data exposure and checking. Addressing these problems usually requires a lot of careful testing and secure data management. We both agree that it’s just a testament to the importance of having others check potential edge cases that you wouldn’t have otherwise thought to check.
